LOAD DATA

All data was collected anonymously which means that a no point it is possible to allocate the recorded information to an individual. However, as with all anonymous data, the risk of identification remains if the reported number of participants are small and a lot of information is known about the individuals in the source population. Although both does not necessarily apply to the data analyzed here, I chose to upload separated data sets in randomly allocated orders of observations. This allows full replication of the results in the manuscript but avoids the allocation of health data od N-of-1 data to individuals in the very unlikely event that individuals should be re-identified by demographic data.

Code 
# Load data from individual N-of-1 studies
## Mindfulness Breathing
ASIP_data_Nof1_MB <- read.csv("../data/ASIP_data_Nof1_MB.csv")

## Box Breathing
ASIP_data_Nof1_BB <- read.csv("../data/ASIP_data_Nof1_BB.csv")

ASIP_data_Nof1_MB_and_BB <- rbind(ASIP_data_Nof1_MB,
                                  ASIP_data_Nof1_BB)
Code 
# Load data from baseline REDCap Questionnaire
## Demographic Data
data_REDCap_table1_MB_and_BB_dem <- read.csv("../data/data_REDCap_table1_MB_and_BB_dem.csv")

## Health Data
data_REDCap_table1_MB_and_BB_health <- read.csv("../data/data_REDCap_table1_MB_and_BB_health.csv")

## Sex and Stress
## Since sex and stress is also part of the N-of-1 data sets, they are stored in random order separately from the other data sets for anonymity reasons.
data_REDCap_table1_MB_and_BB_sex_and_stress <- read.csv("../data/data_REDCap_table1_MB_and_BB_sex_and_stress.csv")

1. DESCRIPTIVE ANALYSES

1.1. REDCap Data

Table 1

Descriptive statistics of variables assessed at baseline are calculated. As mentioned above, to ensure participant anonymity by preventing (unlikely) re-identification, information used to describe the cohort is stored in seperate, randomly sorted dataset. For easy use, all three datasets are combined here. However, this means that values stored as one observation come from different persons. THEREFORE, ANY ANALYSES OTHER THAN DESCRIPTIVE STATISTICS DOES NOT(!!!) YIELD MEANINGFUL RESULTS! The data can only be used to replicate the descriptive statistics presented in the manuscript. #### Prep Data Set

Code 
data_REDCap_table1_MB <- cbind(filter(data_REDCap_table1_MB_and_BB_dem,
                                     intervention == 1),
                              filter(data_REDCap_table1_MB_and_BB_health,
                                     intervention == 1),
                              filter(data_REDCap_table1_MB_and_BB_sex_and_stress,
                                     intervention == 1))
data_REDCap_table1_MB <- fct_polish_REDCap_data(data_REDCap_table1_MB) |> data.frame()


data_REDCap_table1_BB <- cbind(filter(data_REDCap_table1_MB_and_BB_dem,
                                     intervention == 2),
                              filter(data_REDCap_table1_MB_and_BB_health,
                                     intervention == 2),
                              filter(data_REDCap_table1_MB_and_BB_sex_and_stress,
                                     intervention == 2))
data_REDCap_table1_BB <- fct_polish_REDCap_data(data_REDCap_table1_BB) |> data.frame()

3. AGGREGATED TRIALS ANALYSIS

To estimate the intervention effects on the population level, all data from each intervention was analyzed together. The Bayesian multilevel model as used for the individual analyses was extended to acknowledge the nested structure of the individual trials.

Define Formulas

Daily Stress

Code 
formula_bayes_daily_stress <- as.formula(
  survey1_question1_response ~ intervention_period + ar(p = 1) + (intervention_period |
                                                                    manuscript_ID)
)

Expected stress on next day

Code 
formula_bayes_next_day <- as.formula(
  survey1_question2_response ~ intervention_period + ar(p = 1) + (intervention_period |
                                                                    manuscript_ID)
)
